{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659682"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20883"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20883"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96848"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13758"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79463"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11793"},{"type":"tags","id":"11794"},{"type":"tags","id":"12708"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33149"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33151"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96848"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMarfan syndrome is an autosomal dominant connective tissue disorder with characteristic manifestations in multiple organ systems.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the fundamental pathophysiological mechanism in Marfan syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Overproduction of glycosaminoglycans","Deficiency of elastin production","Mutation in TGF-\u03b2 type II receptor","Defective collagen synthesis","Abnormal fibrillin-1 causing excessive TGF-\u03b2 activity"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMarfan syndrome results from mutations in the FBN1 gene that encodes \u003Cstrong\u003Eabnormal fibrillin-1 causing excessive TGF-\u03b2 activity\u003C/strong\u003E. Fibrillin-1 forms microfibrils in the extracellular matrix that normally bind and regulate TGF-\u03b2. Defective fibrillin-1 leads to structural weakness in connective tissues and dysregulated TGF-\u03b2 signalling, driving the disease manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlternative mechanisms that are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverproduction of glycosaminoglycans\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in mucopolysaccharidoses, not Marfan syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeficiency of elastin production\u003C/strong\u003E characterizes conditions like cutis laxa and Williams syndrome. In Marfan syndrome, fibrillin-1 abnormalities affect the scaffold for elastin, but elastin synthesis itself remains intact\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMutation in TGF-\u03b2 type II receptor\u003C/strong\u003E is found in Loeys-Dietz syndrome, which shares features with Marfan syndrome but has a different genetic basis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefective collagen synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E underlies Ehlers-Danlos syndrome variants, not Marfan syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMarfan syndrome typically presents with tall stature, arachnodactyly (long fingers), joint hypermobility, aortic root dilation, mitral valve prolapse, and ectopia lentis (lens dislocation). Aortic dissection represents the most serious potential complication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Marfan syndrome is caused by mutations in the FBN1 gene that encodes fibrillin-1, an extracellular glycoprotein essential for microfibril formation.","The pathogenesis of Marfan syndrome involves both structural weakening of connective tissues and excessive TGF-\u03b2 signalling.","Clinical manifestations of Marfan syndrome primarily affect the skeletal, cardiovascular, and ocular systems."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 148 -149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79463"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20883"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79463"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T08:41:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T08:42:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13758"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96848"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11793"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Mendelian disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-12T20:19:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T20:19:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"t